post_text: Today is Patriot Day. Observed annually on September 11, Patriot Day honors and remembers those who were injured or killed during the attacks on the U.S. on September 11, 2001. The flags of the United States and the state of Florida will be flown from sunrise to sunset at half-staff today to commemorate this national day of service and remembrance. #NeverForget

post_text: Did you know? The Tampa Bay Network to End Hunger has expanded Meals on Wheels For Kids into Clearwater. The program, which provides an alternative opportunity for Pinellas County students to access meals, utilizes PCS buses and local volunteers to deliver meal packs and boxes of shelf-stable foods around the St. Petersburg and Clearwater communities. For more information, including how to sign up, visit networktoendhunger.org/mow4kids/.

Congressman Charlie Crist paid a visit to Largo High School to present students and staff with a display from the National Archives in Washington, DC commemorating the 100th anniversary of the passage of the 19th Amendment to the US Constitution, which ended gender-based voting restrictions in the US.

This visit and presentation commended the students, who started a school-based effort last year to register eligible students to vote, for their work in increasing youth voter turnout and breaking down voting barriers. Students plan to continue efforts this year.

Thank you, Congressman Crist for your recognition of these students. We are so #PCSProud of their leadership and community service üéâ

Thank you Spectrum Bay News 9 for recognizing Leila G. Davis Elementary educator Erin Ornot as an A+ Teacher. We are so #PCSProud to have teachers and staff like Erin who work with students to maximize their potential.

Erin says, "I love when I see the kids struggling with something and we work on it together in a different way and all of a sudden their eyes just pop open wider and you'll see that light bulb go off because they get it. They just get it and those are my favorite moments. When you see them recognize that they were just successful with something. That's my inspiration." See the full story ‚§µÔ∏è

During the 2020 Back-to-School Sales Tax Holiday, Aug. 7-9, qualifying items will be exempt from tax, including certain school supplies selling for $15 or less per item; clothing, footwear, and certain accessories selling for $60 or less per item; and the first $1,000 of the sales price of personal computers and certain computer-related accessories purchased for noncommercial home or personal use.

For more information and a list of qualifying items, visit https://floridarevenue.com/backtoschool.

The first meeting of the Parent-Guardian Connection was held last night and the topic was "The Emotional and Mental Wellbeing of our Children", presented by Dr. Carleah East, Clinical Psychotherapist. Dr. East had some amazing, relevant and practical suggestions for taking care of our families and ourselves. In case you weren't able to attend, the recording is available at www.pcsb.org/parentadvocacy

The Parent Guardian Connection has been created to provide a virtual forum for parents and guardians to connect, to be supported, to share resources, and to engage. Stay tuned for information about our next meeting.

post_text:
Ms. Becky Bride, recently retired mathematics teacher at Palm Harbor University High School, was recently awarded the Presidential Awards for Excellence in Mathematics and Science Teaching. This award is one of the nation's highest honors for STEM teachers, and we are so #PCSProud to see one of our educators be recognized among the small group from across the nation.

Ms. Bride says, "This award is the pinnacle of my career. I am honored and truly humbled. This award was not possible without the amazing students I have had the privilege of teaching, my colleagues, the administrators who supported me, and the support of my family." Congratulations, Ms. Bride!

Read more: ow.ly/R5ZM50AQDCG #PCSShines #MyPCS

July 29 at 3:49 PM ¬∑

Westfield Countryside has partnered with us to host an in-person Stuff the Bus school supply drive. You can support students in need by donating supplies at the colorful display on the second floor of the shopping center anytime until Aug. 15.

Or join us at Westfield Countryside for a day-long Stuff the Bus event on Friday, July 31 from 11 a.m. - 7 p.m. Donations can be dropped off at the display inside or drive through our contactless drop-off area outside near the Pinellas County Schools Bus. LAST DAY: The deadline to select a ReOpening learning option is today, July 27, at 5:00 p.m. EST. Families can make their choice by logging in with their parent portal account to reservation.pcsb.org.

Need help with your parent portal login information?

Get in touch with staff who can help using one of these three options:
1. Email a copy or photo of your valid photo ID to StudentAssignment@PCSB.org with your username and/or password request.

2. Reach out to your student's school directly for assistance. All school contact information is available here: pcsb.org/schools

3. Submit a Let's Talk message via the PCS website: pcsb.org/domain/211.

post_text: IMPORTANT REOPENING UPDATE: The superintendent will be making a recommendation to delay the start of school until August 24. This recommendation will be made to the Pinellas County School Board at the board meeting on July 28 and will require approval. The goal of this delay would be to allow teachers and other staff additional time to plan for the school year in response to changes implemented due to COVID-19. Please note: this recommendation would not change the dates for Thanksgiving, spring and winter breaks. Thank you for your patience, flexibility and support during this unprecedented time. For more information, please visit: http://ow.ly/JnMw50AEzrh

post_text: In 2017, a group of Clearwater High students was completing their Civil Rights Tour through the south and they were determined to meet Rep. John Lewis. They had tried to set up an appointment via his office but it didn‚Äôt seem to work. While in D.C that year, they decided to just go to his office on Capitol Hill. When they arrived, Rep. Lewis was opening the door to leave. Rep. Lewis graciously spent about 30-45 minutes speaking with the students about an array of issues and encouraged them to always do what was right. www.pcsb.org/chscivilrightstour

post_text: IMPORTANT UPDATE: Pinellas County Schools is aware of the positive COVID-19 cases that have been confirmed at Spectrum Field, the Philadelphia Phillies spring training facility. We spoke to venue management today to understand how this might affect our scheduled graduation ceremonies. At this time, the Phillies are thoroughly disinfecting the facility and our ceremonies are still moving forward as planned. We will continue to monitor the situation with Spectrum Field officials and will post updates as needed.
shared_text:
Pinellas County Schools
June 17 at 3:30 PM ¬∑

It's time to celebrate! Live graduation ceremonies for the graduating class of 2020 will take place the week of July 7th at Spectrum Field. Please note that these ceremonies will have a special, abbreviated format that will help ensure the health and well-being of all participants. To review the full schedule and ceremony procedures, please click here: http://ow.ly/uhBD50AaArE

Edit: Please note that in-person graduation ceremonies are not open to the public outside of the allotted four guests per student to ensure the health and safety of all students, families and staff members.

Could your child benefit from extra learning this summer? Summer Bridge programs will be virtual and available to all students in grades K-12. Apply NOW at https://reservation.pcsb.org/

Most elementary and middle school programs will take place Monday-Thursday, June 8-July 16. Most high school programs will take place Monday-Thursday, June 22-July 16.

Elementary school students will engage in weekly themed lessons and participate in virtual field trips, while building math, science and language arts skills. Middle school students will focus on reading, math and social studies. High school students will focus on math and/or reading skills and prepare for the July ACT.
